07-stikkord-samling/dat320/fetch-and-add.description:
Fetch-and-Add locks (ticket locks) are correct and fair, making them better than TAS/CAS for fairness-sensitive scenarios. Still, they spin, so for long waits or high contention, prefer blocking locks.One-liner:
A lock built on the atomic fetch_and_add instruction, providing FIFO fairness by assigning tickets to threads.
Primitive:
fetch_and_add(addr, inc) atomically: Returns the old value at addr.
Adds inc to addr. Lock idea (ticket lock): Maintain two counters: next_ticket (next ticket number to give out).
now_serving (ticket currently being served). my_ticket = fetch_and_add(&amp;next_ticket, 1); while (now_serving != my_ticket) { // spin
}
Run
now_serving++;
Run volatile int next_ticket = 0;
volatile int now_serving = 0; void lock() { int my_ticket = fetch_and_add(&amp;next_ticket, 1); while (now_serving != my_ticket) { // spin }
} void unlock() { now_serving++;
} Yes: Mutual exclusion guaranteed because each thread waits for its ticket to be served. Fair? Yes (FIFO order).
Threads acquire the lock in the order they requested it. Spins: Still busy-waiting, but: No starvation.
Reduces contention compared to TAS/CAS because each thread spins on its own ticket condition rather than hammering the same memory location. Cache behavior: Better than TAS/CAS under heavy load, but still involves polling. Fairness: FIFO ordering prevents starvation.
Simplicity: Easy to implement with one atomic instruction.
Predictable: Good for real-time or fairness-sensitive workloads. Busy-waiting: Wastes CPU cycles if critical sections are long.
Cache traffic: Still present, though less severe than TAS/CAS.
Requires two shared counters.
