07-stikkord-samling/dat320/yield-based-l.description:
Yield-based locks are a quick fix to reduce CPU waste in spin locks but remain unfair and inefficient under heavy contention. For long waits, prefer blocking locks.One-liner:
A spin lock variant that uses the OS yield() primitive to reduce CPU waste when the lock is busy.
Instead of tight spinning (busy-waiting), a thread that fails to acquire the lock calls yield(), asking the scheduler to move it from running to ready state.
This gives other threads a chance to run, reducing wasted CPU cycles compared to pure spin locks.
void lock() { while (test_and_set(&amp;flag) == 1) { yield(); // voluntarily give up CPU }
} void unlock() { flag = 0;
} Yes: Mutual exclusion is preserved because the lock acquisition still uses an atomic operation (e.g., Test-and-Set). Fair? Not guaranteed.
Yield reduces CPU hogging but does not enforce FIFO ordering. Starvation is still possible. Better than pure spin locks under contention because threads don’t burn entire time slices spinning.
Issues: Can cause unnecessary context switches if many threads repeatedly yield.
Still not as efficient as blocking locks (park/unpark) for long waits. Reduces CPU waste compared to busy-waiting.
Simple to implement if OS provides yield(). No fairness guarantee.
Context-switch overhead can be high with many contenders.
Still unsuitable for long critical sections.
